Dear All,

Our original implementation regarding implementation at UUM is now complete, please review details below carefully as this is has been a complex engagement:


1.       All project documentation, SOW, sign off and profiles including contacts at the customer site can be found at UUM account level https://imprivata.my.salesforce.com/00180000010LWda

2.       Support calls should be received via the acting partner involved which is Complete Solution Finder, primary support contact is Steven Loew, his details can be found in SF at https://imprivata.my.salesforce.com/0033000000PjK1R who is ICE trained.

3.       The only outstanding work against the original SOW is the delivery of an onsite ICE course at the end user, UUM.  Professional services are currently in discussion with the customer as to when this will be delivered.

Issues


1.       UUM are experiencing several issues with end user success due to an unmanaged estate of end users.  They do not have managed control of the end user devices or software such as OS, internet toolbars and protection software.  This is something to be aware of if in receipt of support calls relating to the same.  Both CSFinder (the partner), professional services and Imprivata have been involved in discussions with UUM regarding this and CSFinder are currently working with UUM on our recommendations that the end user estate must comply with the remit of our supported configurations guidelines.

Kind regards
Sam

column20: Tomorrow at 11:00AM: CLOUD LIVE! Virtual Event  + Gift Card Giveaways
column22:
CLOUD LIVE! Virtual Event - March 20, 2014 8:00AM - 3:30PM PST 



CLOUD LIVE! kicks off with our first virtual event on March 20, 2014 from 8:00AM - 3:30PM PST.  Our 2013 virtual event series was a huge success with over 700 sales partners in attendance.  With a new enhanced learning environment, the 2014 events are not to be missed!



Reserve Your Spot:

http://www.ustream.tv/channel/cloud-live-march-20th-2014#li=7846889&cs=jFHl5%2FSMgDIDS9WV30AKbQ%3D%3D



Live Sessions Agenda 



8:30AM PST - Keynote from Andrew Pryfogle 



9:30AM PST - Strategic IT Mapping in Practice 

We rolled out our Strategic IT Mapping process early in 2013. It outlined a process of helping a customer determine their strategic direction for IT before determining the right course of action. Bottom line, Cloud calls for consultative selling more than any other solution we deliver. Hear from some of the leading thinkers around DaaS and how they are positioning these solutions as strategic IT initiatives. Most importantly, hear how this approach is landing big deals and how you can do the same.

 

11:00AM PST - The Anatomy of a Cloud Contact Center Deal 

Contact Centers continue to migrate to the Cloud in mass. This adoption is resulting in big wins, but where are these deals being found, who is signing the contract, what are the key decision points, and how can you win in this space? Hear from leading Cloud Contact Center experts about how this accelerated market is presenting big opportunities in the channel. 



12:30PM PST - Real Cloud Wins 

We all have theory coming out our ears. It’s time for some more real cloud wins…real battle stories of deals fought for and won from those who were in the trenches. Hear from suppliers and sales partners as they team to tell these great stories. Bottom line, you have a prospect that looks, walks, and talks like one of these wins. Learn what it will take to create your own winning stories. 



2:00PM PST - Where Cloud & Network Meet 

We’ve known for some time that cloud would drive a bigger appetite for bandwidth, and in fact, we’ve seen an explosion in cable and fiber sales to feed that demand. Many providers are now layering intelligence on the network that was not previously available. Learn how you can dramatically increase your network sales by leveraging these new offers that reflect the new cloud economy. 



Sign Up Here:

http://www.ustream.tv/channel/cloud-live-march-20th-2014#li=7846890&cs=jFHl5%2FSMgDIDS9WV30AKbQ%3D%3D

column20: Key Factors Influencing the Choice of Distribution Channels for Mobile Apps
column22:
Hello,

I'm conducting research for my Master's thesis in Industrial Engineering at Lappeenranta University of Technology in Finland. Your responses to this short survey will assist with my research on key factors influencing the choice of distribution channels for mobile apps.

It will take about three minutes to complete the survey; please reply by March 31, 2014.

You are one of 5,000 software developers I have randomly selected from the App Store, Google Play, and Windows Phone listings. Your opinions are very important to this study.

I will share the results of the study with you if you include your email address at the end of the survey.

I've invited you to fill out the form Key factors influencing the choice of distribution channels for mobile apps. To fill it out, visit:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/19vY72NwPeUBhfH95_y8GAXurpWLoH2mzccNrHZJyrQQ/viewform

Best Regards,
Susanne Lumme
susanne.lumme@lut.fi

column86:
Once you log into the Cortext Admin Center please go down to Configuration and click on "Manage Admins". This account you add will be separate from the account they log into Cortext with on their mobile device and is meant only for the Admin Center. Once you add them you can then check off what privileges you would like them to have. In this case, if you want them to add users you would select "Users" only and they would be able to invite new users.

Closing case as I have not heard back from the customer after multiple attempts to communicate and I have answered their question above.

column20: Selling Your Android App Just Got Easier with Apptopia!
column22:
Hello Hello!

My name is Tess and I’m part of the team at Apptopia. We broker the sale of mobile app ownership and compile competitive analysis on mobile data. 

Our Mission: Make App Developers Money

In the last six months, we’ve generated over $1.8 million for developers just like you. With over 900 live listings and more than 1000 apps sold, we are the answer for the developer’s exit strategy concerns. 

We just rolled out a new and improved transfer process and payment process! All payments are now done with the ease of PayPal. Here is a summary of the 5 steps for transfers:

Step 1 (initial payment)

The buyer must submit payment for 50% of the final acquisition price. 

Step 2 (app transfer)

This is where the app(s) get transferred from one developer account to another on the app store level.  

Step 3 (transfer verification)

Essentially, we ask that buyers connect their new developer account to Apptopia after the transfer so that we can verify for 100% the app(s) purchased do in fact live in the buyer’s account.  

Step 4 (final payment)

Now that we have verified the transfer is 100% complete, we require payment of the final 50% of the acquisition price.  

Step 5 (complete!)

After the final payment is received, source code and app assets all become available for download for the buyer.

For a more in depth and detailed explanation of this, head over to 
http://track.apptopia.com/?xt=ZO1hpIHjXJU0oTQ2XIt0pTM6Xk9unS9zXyRioTDhoSxtXyZhnE9ioy9wpIZ0XJHiLSR0LE1gLJofoSR5nIHgpO1tnyCfpTVtnzZyLJUfoTVhK2Hlok8%3Du&xi=support@cortext.com
and read up!

Get Involved!

Let us help you make money. To sell your app, head over to www.apptopia.com and sign up. Be ready to go in 5 minutes! 

Questions

You can reach out and ask me anything. I promise I'm not a robot and I'm always here to help (literally, always, 24/7, 365).

Feel free to reply to this email. 

Cheers,

Tess

column20: Tap for Tap SDK3 - Big Improvements
column22:
Hi

I’m Jessica Purdy, developer outreach specialist for Tap for Tap. I’m sure you get lots of emails from ad networks like mine, so I’ll keep this brief. I’m writing you to ask you to check out Tap for Tap’s newly redesigned SDK3. http://in.tapfortap.com/info/sgn/sdk3

Tap for Tap is a small team of app-loving developers and marketers who’ve built a mobile advertising platform with 2 major components:

1. Ad network focused on app monetization via high ecpm interstitial ads (banners and app wall also available). 
2. Cross-promotion tap exchange - generate perpetual installs with no effort.

Our newly redesigned interstitial ad units are producing eCPMs in game apps as high as $15 and are definitely worth a test in your app mix. 

Using a tap exchange in your ad mix is a very simple way to get new users for your app on an ongoing basis with little effort. We also have a great self-promotion tool that allows you to promote your own portfolio of apps or is ideal for urging users to upgrade to paid versions of your app.

If you have a few minutes for a chat, I’d love to connect you with Taylor, our customer service guy as soon as possible. If you’re interested, please let me know or respond to me or Taylor@Tapfortap.com directly.

If you’re not interested in our services but have other ideas for what you’d like to see from a product like ours, don’t hesitate to tell us. We’re the kind of nimble, dynamic team ready to do what it takes to earn your business.

Thank you for your time

-Jessica

More Info:

As always, you can pick and choose which elements you’d like to use. We both offer SDK and S2S integrations for our paid promotion services.

Tap for Tap is also fully integrated with Corona SDK, Unity 3d, Appcelerator/Titanium, Adobe Air, Basic4Android, Cocos 2d. We are also compatible with Admob Mediation, AdWhirl and MoPub. Check out our documentation at http://in.tapfortap.com/info/sgn/documentation

If you’re looking for an example of a few great apps on our network, please check out Mind Feud by Monkey Bin on Android or iOS. Also take a look at Face Juggler on iOS as it’s a personal favorite among our staff. :)
--

Jessica Purdy
Tap for Tap
210-852 Fort Street
Victoria, B.C. Canada
V8W 1H8


To remove yourself from this email list go to http://sugar.tapfortap.com/index.php?entryPoint=removeme&identifier=afef1160-3b8b-ffcc-92a4-524e2f784901

column20: RE: Computer Policy settings not carrying to endpoint
column22:
Same thing happened to me at Sisters of Charity in Billings in June.  See attached for more details.  If you know how you set up the policies, I think it's time to open a high priority case.  When I was working with Yuri, he said it was workflow dependent.  I now question that.  There is a case number in the attached that can be referenced: we either need to open a new case or reopen the one in the attached email.  Definitely need Dev looking at this.

Thanks,
Allan

Allan Tygert
Senior Implementation Engineer
atygert@imprivata.com<mailto:atygert@imprivata.com>
512.537.1959
Skype: tygertap

From: John Delcalzo
Sent: Tuesday, August 27, 2013 3:39 PM
To: Services; se; Support
Subject: Computer Policy settings not carrying to endpoint

I hadn't heard of this type of thing in a while so I thought I'd mention:

Doing a PoC with 4.8 HF4. Endpoint is W7 64 bit. Setup Fast user switching for epic between endpoint and citrix server policies and it was all 100% right (I checked 5 times).  However the citrix session was still getting killed between user switches. After much frustration we opened trace and saw that the endpoint was calling citrix to disconnect the session on switch. When we looked at the config view on trace we found that the local computer did indeed have the setting to disconnect on user switch. One last time I verified that it was in the right policy.

It was.

I went back to computer policy of the endpoint, unchecked fast user switching, checked disconnect citrix client on user switch, saved and synced the endpoint. The trace config then showed the opposite of what I had just set in policy. *urgh*. Then I went and set everything back the way it is supposed to be, synced with server and the trace showed the right settings, finally.  I ran my epic user switch and everything was fine.

Anyone seen this lately? Is this supposed to be fixed or is this a known *occasional* bug?

Also, has anyone noticed the SSO APG test doesn't always work? Test won't recognize a login window (OWA, for example) but if I deploy the profile everything works great. This happened to me on two different applications.


John Delcalzo
Sales Engineer
Imprivata, Inc.

column22:
Whan that aprill with his shoures soote
The droghte of march hath perced to the roote,
And bathed every veyne in swich licour
Of which vertu engendred is the flour;
Whan zephirus eek with his sweete breeth
Inspired hath in every holt and heeth
Tendre croppes, and the yonge sonne
Hath in the ram his halve cours yronne,
And smale foweles maken melodye,
That slepen al the nyght with open ye
(so priketh hem nature in hir corages);
Thanne longen folk to goon on pilgrimages,
And palmeres for to seken straunge strondes,
To ferne halwes, kowthe in sondry londes;
And specially from every shires ende
Of engelond to caunterbury they wende,
The hooly blisful martir for to seke,
That hem hath holpen whan that they were seeke.

column20: new transferring cases to services protocol
column22:
Hi all,

I have been requested to manage the services queue with Judy R, and as such we're trying to come up with a new process when transferring cases from support to services. While this is going on (writing up the official process etc.) please follow these steps when transferring cases to services:


1.       Email myself and Judy R

2.       Include case#

3.       What has been done so far (if anything)

4.       Transfer case to service QUEUE

5.       Case status is irrelevant, but please note change case status to services does not assign the case to services.

In the near future (within a week or two) I should be providing a more formal presentation of the new process and discussing with you guys if it makes sense and so on so forth.

In the meantime, please follow the above steps, shouldn't take that much time and will help us as a department have a more seamless transition from the customer perspective.

Thanks,

Brian

column20: Let us give you a reason to test Tap for Tap
column22:
Hi

This is Jessica from Tap for Tap checking in with you. I emailed you a little while ago about your app, Cortext. I’d love to have a chat to give you some reasons to test out Tap for Tap with Cortext or any other apps you have in your portfolio.

In 2013 we’ve just passed 1 million installs generated for our developers, who now number over 9000 in total across all categories on Android and iOS. I’d love it if you’d sign up for an account at http://in.tapfortap.com/info/melr and take a deeper look.

Tap for Tap offers the following services in the user acquisition and app monetization areas:

Free Tap Exchange - cross promote with other apps for free
Paid Promotion - buy traffic/users for your app at great rates (CPM, CPC or CPII)
Self Promotion - promote your own apps
Ad Monetization - Show ads earn great ecpms

As always, you can pick and choose which elements you’d like to use. We both offer SDK and S2S integrations for our paid promotion services.

Tap for Tap is also fully integrated with Corona SDK, Unity 3d, Appcelerator/Titanium, Adobe Air, Basic4Android, Cocos 2d. We are also compatible with Admob Mediation, AdWhirl and MoPub. Check out our documentation at http://in.tapfortap.com/info/melr/documentation

If you’re looking for an example of a few great apps on our network, please check out Mind Feud by Monkey Bin on Android or iOS https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=no.monkeybin.mindfeud&hl=en. Also take a look at Face Juggler on iOS as it’s a personal favorite among our staff https://itunes.apple.com/ca/app/face-juggler-free/id482473443?mt=8. :)

I’d love to give you some more reasons test out Tap for Tap in your app. Do you have a few moments for a Skype with Taylor (taylor@tapfortap.com) from our developer advocate team in the next few days? Please let me know and I’ll set something up ASAP or feel free to reach out to him directly.

Thanks for taking the time to read this. I really appreciate it.

Best
-Jessica

Sent from my iPhone

On Jun 19, 2013, at 4:24 PM, "Brianna Sionne" <bsionne@IMPRIVATA.com> wrote:
Hi Paramjeet,
 
It sounds like you may not have push notifications turned on for Cortext.  Please take the following steps to fix on your phone:
 
1.	On your iPhone, go to “Settings”
2.	Select “Notifications”
3.	Scroll down to “Cortext”
4.	Set the following notifications (image below)
a.	Notification Center – On
b.	Alert Style – Alerts
c.	Badge App Icon - On
d.	Sounds – On
e.	View in Lock Screen – On
 
5.	Additionally, in the Cortext App, confirm that you have sounds turned on under “Settings > Message Alerts”
 
Please let me know if this rectifies the issue and do not hesitate to reach me should you have further questions.
 
Thanks!
 
Brianna

column20: FW: Additonal Information for Modality Issue
column22:
Ok Guys,
We captured another instance of the modality issue we are having in Tennessee. See comments below.

We have to get this resolved. Beginning June 10th, St. Thomas Hospital will be moving into full enrollment mode and we don't want to use the temporary fix of using Z class devices for enrollment. Also, the way I see it, this modality issue will prohibit us from moving Baptist Hospital off the 021 FW to 026.12 because we are asking the users to re-enroll to make the change happen. If this modality condition occurs in the Xenith environment, that is all that exists at Baptist. This now becomes a bigger issue. Shaun/Volatire, correct me if I'm wrong on this.

Brian Beer
Sr. Project Manager
Coretek Services
* 248-684-9400 Ext 216
* 734-788-5226 Cell
* brian.beer@coretekservices.com
* 38505 Country Club Drive Suite 210 Farmington Hills MI 48331
*   http://www.coretekservices.com<https://mail.coretekservices.com/owa/redir.aspx?C=b88c4c3ea62c4972b986b21ff34cd6c5&URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.coretekservices.com%2f>
Metro Detroit's 101 Best & Brightest Companies to work for!

From: Shaun Holder
Sent: Thursday, May 30, 2013 10:34 AM
To: Brian Beer
Cc: Ray Jaksic; Voltaire Toledo
Subject: Additonal Information for

Hello,

Lou was able to replicate the Modality Error. I have captured an additional log and screen shots.

The user enrolled using a Xenith on the 26.12 firmware, tapped out, and recieved the Modality error on ever subsequent tap back into the device. I had Lou tap the users badge multiple times while experiencing the modality error, and the times she did this match up with the "authenticate prove id failed" error log at the top of the attached log screenshot.

Hi Rongtao,

I have a potential Cortext customer that would like to know if they could use Hyper-V (Microsoft based) to connect the AD instead of VMware - do you know if this would be a possibility?

Thanks!

Brianna

Brianna Sionne |  Client Services Consultant
Imprivata, Inc | 10 Maguire Road | Lexington MA 02421
O: 781-761-2684
M: 508.472.8898

[Description: Description: Description: cid:image001.png@01CDD214.0D93EEB0]<http://www.imprivata.com/>
column86:
From: Rongtao Fu 
Sent: Friday, May 10, 2013 12:48 PM
To: Brianna Sionne
Cc: Cortext Support
Subject: RE: Hyper-V connection with Cortext

Brianna,
The answer is no. They can't. Cortext Directory Connector shares the same platform as OneSign virtual appliance. Currently only VMWare is officially supported. As a matter of fact, the virtual appliance won't work on Hyper-V. I don't know if Hyper-V is on the future roadmap or not, but currently it's not supported.
Thanks,
-Rongtao

I got a call from Imprivata engineer earlier today who confirmed that the SSO agent inherits proxy settings from system settings. i.e. whatever is configured in IE will be used. This has it pros and cons.



What this means to us is that we need to add a few entries to proxy exceptions list. I will send you a list later today.



Regards

Kris

>are always recognised as local intranet) I was able to launch desktop.

>desktop. Both tests were undertaken using the same user account.

>>        Hi Dave, John,

>>

>>

>>

>>        Just to confirm as long as the reader is mapped via the

>>virtual channel before the login is required from the Windows VDI

>>session then this should (but no guarantees at this stage) work.

>>

>>

>>

>>        What we have seen elsewhere with Citrix is that USB

>>redirection has its own workflow: we have seen some timing issues

>>because the Windows/OneSign UI arrived before the USB device was

>>redirected (VD connection and USB redirection are asynchronous

>>processes). With ICA, if I'm not wrong, USB is redirected only after

>>user is logged in on the VD and not at GINA/CP level so if this is the case it would not work.

>>

>>

>>

>>        There is also the 'tap off' workflow, if the reader is

>>connected to the Windows VDI session then we can initiate a lock or

>>log off but then how the bedside unit handles this I am not sure.

>>

>>

>>

>>        So generally I think that it could be done, but don't assume

>>that it's as easy as it may seem...

>>

>>

>>

>>        The WEBAPI integration will remove all this confusion and

>>streamline the entire authentication process.

>>

>>

>>

>>        Regards,

>>

>>

>>

>>        Matthew

>>

>>

>>

>>        From: Dave Harley <dave.harley@lincor.com<mailto:dave.harley@lincor.com>>

>>        Date: Tuesday, 28 August 2012 11:56

>>        To: John O'Connor <John.O'Connor@northgatemanagedservices.com>

>>        Cc: Matthew Law <mlaw@imprivata.com<mailto:mlaw@imprivata.com>>, Karen Cashman

>><karen.cashman@lincor.com<mailto:karen.cashman@lincor.com>>

>>        Subject: Re: WHSCT

>>

>>

>>

>>        Hi Matt, John,

>>

>>        Just want to synopsis the call I had with Matt.

>>        ( Matt I hope this is what you understood from the call as

>>well... )

>>

>>        * I described the initial connection as follows:

>>        User taps card: Lincor detects a card and launches a Citrix

>>Receiver connection to the citrix XenDesktop mapping the Omnikey RFID

>>through to the citrix server.

>>        The card reader is detected by the Imprivata Citrix One Sign

>>Agent and a card swipe is requests if the card is not visible at the

>>reader and a PIN request is generated.   The user enters the PIN.

>>        The agent authenticates the card/PIN pair and retrieves the login

>>ccredentials and logs into the XenDesktop session.   The Card reader

>>connection is handed to the agent in the Xen Desktop which will be

>>able to query the card reader as needed.

>>        Lincor detects an additional card tap which will cause the

>>Citrix session connection to be terminated.

>>

>>        * The WEBAPI integration will drive the closer integration of

>>the user session and will resolve the two tap or continuous tap

>>requirement present in the initial phase.

>>        A card tap will cause a PIN to locally collected.   Once

>>collected we will use the WEBAPI to citrix xendesktop credentials.

>>Using these credential we will directly log into the xenDesktop

>>session and map the reader into the Desktop so the Desktop agent will

>>have access to the

>>service.   Additional capabilities like card enrolment, password changing

>>etc can also be made available from this WEBAPI.   The delivery of this

>>phase is not yet scheduled.

>>

>>        So for the first phase we would need that the required

>>configuration of the citrix env/Imprivata one sign agent for Citrix be

>>correctly installed and configured.   Hopefully this is in place but on

>>testing, it doesn't appear to be available.

>>

>>        John, as you know Matt is away,  he suggested that you have a

>>contact called Andrew in Imprivata that might be able to help.   Also do

>>you have any Citrix resource to check that the above phase one

>>capability is available and configured?

>>

>>        Regards,

>>

>>        Dave

>>

>>

>>        Hi Dave, John,

>>

>>

>>

>>        Just to confirm as long as the reader is mapped via the

>>virtual channel before the login is required from the Windows VDI

>>session then this should (but no guarantees at this stage) work.

>>

>>

>>

>>        What we have seen elsewhere with Citrix is that USB

>>redirection has its own workflow: we have seen some timing issues

>>because the Windows/OneSign UI arrived before the USB device was

>>redirected (VD connection and USB redirection are asynchronous

>>processes). With ICA, if I'm not wrong, USB is redirected only after

>>user is logged in on the VD and not at GINA/CP level so if this is the case it would not work.

>>

>>

>>

>>        There is also the 'tap off' workflow, if the reader is

>>connected to the Windows VDI session then we can initiate a lock or

>>log off but then how the bedside unit handles this I am not sure.

>>

>>

>>

>>        So generally I think that it could be done, but don't assume

>>that it's as easy as it may seem...

>>

>>

>>

>>        The WEBAPI integration will remove all this confusion and

>>streamline the entire authentication process.

>>

>>

>>

>>        Regards,

>>

>>

>>

>>        Matthew

>>

>>

>>

>>        From: Dave Harley <dave.harley@lincor.com>

>>        Date: Tuesday, 28 August 2012 11:56

>>        To: John O'Connor <John.O'Connor@northgatemanagedservices.com>

>>        Cc: Matthew Law <mlaw@imprivata.com>, Karen Cashman

>><karen.cashman@lincor.com>

>>        Subject: Re: WHSCT

>>

>>

>>        Hi Matt, John,

>>

>>        Just want to synopsis the call I had with Matt.

>>        ( Matt I hope this is what you understood from the call as

>>well... )

>>

>>        * I described the initial connection as follows:

>>        User taps card: Lincor detects a card and launches a Citrix

>>Receiver connection to the citrix XenDesktop mapping the Omnikey RFID

>>through to the citrix server.

>>        The card reader is detected by the Imprivata Citrix One Sign

>>Agent and a card swipe is requests if the card is not visible at the

>>reader and a PIN request is generated.   The user enters the PIN.

>>        The agent authenticates the card/PIN pair and retrieves the login

>>ccredentials and logs into the XenDesktop session.   The Card reader

>>connection is handed to the agent in the Xen Desktop which will be

>>able to query the card reader as needed.

>>        Lincor detects an additional card tap which will cause the

>>Citrix session connection to be terminated.

>>

>>        * The WEBAPI integration will drive the closer integration of

>>the user session and will resolve the two tap or continuous tap

>>requirement present in the initial phase.

>>        A card tap will cause a PIN to locally collected.   Once

>>collected we will use the WEBAPI to citrix xendesktop credentials.

>>Using these credential we will directly log into the xenDesktop

>>session and map the reader into the Desktop so the Desktop agent will

>>have access to the

>>service.   Additional capabilities like card enrolment, password changing

>>etc can also be made available from this WEBAPI.   The delivery of this

>>phase is not yet scheduled.

>>

>>        So for the first phase we would need that the required

>>configuration of the citrix env/Imprivata one sign agent for Citrix be

>>correctly installed and configured.   Hopefully this is in place but on

>>testing, it doesn't appear to be available.

>>

>>        John, as you know Matt is away,  he suggested that you have a

>>contact called Andrew in Imprivata that might be able to help.   Also do

>>you have any Citrix resource to check that the above phase one

>>capability is available and configured?

>>

>>        Regards,

>>

>>        Dave

Subject: Primelending - Imprivata 

Hi Peter,

I have a couple of questions for you regarding PrimeLending.

They have purchased Vasco tokens and now have the appropriate AM license to rollout this technology.  One thing that they noticed during testing is that the end user does not have the ability to set their own PIN for two factor.  It appears that they must have the help desk actually set the PIN for the end user which is not secure.  I said this did not sound right and they must be doing something wrong.  Can you please confirm that their users do have the ability to set their own PIN for the two-factor solution and that they do not need the separate self-service portal in order to do this?  I understand that the self-service portal is needed in order for end users to reset their own passwords from One Sign and One Sign Anywhere.

Please let me know if you have the answer to this question or if you can point me to the appropriate person who can answer this for me.

Thank you!

Heather Mayabb

column20: RE: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out
column22:
Hi Renato,

Just wondering if you have any updates on this issue?

Thanks,

Paul

From: Renato Menezes [mailto:rmenezes@IMPRIVATA.com]
Sent: April-22-13 10:42 AM
To: Paul Srisoontorn
Cc: Support
Subject: RE: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out

Thanks Paul. Yes, we do have engineering looking at the issue. I will relay the information to them.

Thanks,
Renato

From: Paul Srisoontorn [mailto:psrisoontorn@teradici.com]
Sent: Monday, April 22, 2013 1:39 PM
To: Renato Menezes
Cc: Support
Subject: RE: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out

Hi Renato,

Do you have someone from Engineering that is currently investigating this issue on your side? It looks like something has changed in OneSign 4.7 that is causing this issue. The Zero Client doesn't touch the "Invert Wiegand" setting at all in FW 4.1. The log seems to indicate that the OneSign  Agent is the one that modified the "Invert Wiegand" setting on the reader. Please feel free to give my contact info to the appropriate engineers from Imprivata so that we discuss this issue further.

Thanks,

Paul

From: Renato Menezes [mailto:rmenezes@IMPRIVATA.com]
Sent: April-19-13 5:35 AM
To: Paul Srisoontorn
Cc: Support
Subject: RE: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out

Hello Paul,

Thanks for the information you have sent. We already have a corresponding Imprivata case, case # 71683. I would like to forward to you some communication from customer previously about the "Invert Wiegand" setting and some observations. Please see attached correspondence with customer. Also, the latest update, as of yesterday is that customer found out that if they revert back to OneSign agent 4.6, the issue no longer occurs. Also, if they attach the reader to regular PCs, the issue does not occur even on the latest versions of the OneSign (4.7.7) agent.

Thanks for all your assistance Paul.
Renato

From: Paul Srisoontorn [mailto:psrisoontorn@teradici.com]
Sent: Thursday, April 18, 2013 8:08 PM
To: Renato Menezes
Subject: RE: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out

Note: If you need more info from me regarding this issue, please feel free to contact me at: 604-628-1235. I usually get in the office by 10am PST. Our office is located in Burnaby BC, Canada.

Paul


From: Paul Srisoontorn
Sent: April-18-13 4:23 PM
To: 'rmenezes@imprivata.com'
Subject: FW: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out

Hi Renato,

I'm a FW engineer from Teradici. I'm currently investigating an issue that you opened with Teradici (Ticket 15134-12565).
According to the "4.1 tera2 log" that the customer submitted, it looks like the "Invert Wiegand" setting on the reader was modified while in session which caused the card ID data to be inverted.
From the log, the last successful tap-in happened at 04/16/2013, 14:34:37:
The card ID read by the Zero Client is: 023087F3
          MGMT_PROXIMITY :active_processing: CARD_INSERTED - VID: 0xC27, PID: 0x3BFA, ID (26 bits): 023087F3
The next tap-out happened at 04/16/2013, 14:36:51:
The card ID read by the OneSign agent on tap-out is: 01CF780C
          MGMT_OSVCHAN :mgmt_osvchan_prox_sink_resident_badge_notify: card ID: 01CF780C
The log indicates that while in session, the Invert Weigand Data setting on the reader was changed from "On" to "Off" which caused the card ID data to be inverted:
01CF780C = 01110011110111100000001100b
023087F3 = 10001100001000011111110011b
Note: The Zero Client doesn't touch the reader configuration while in session. The OneSign agent is the one that is responsible for configuring the reader in session. This could be an OneSign agent bug.
I talked to Michael Michlin from Imprivata about this and he would like me to open a case with Imprivata so that the appropriate engineers can look into this issue. Could you please help me open a case with Imprivata for this issue? Please see email below for more info.

Thanks,
Paul

From: Michael Michlin [mailto:mmichlin@IMPRIVATA.com]
Sent: April-18-13 3:36 PM
To: Paul Srisoontorn
Subject: RE: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out

Hi Paul,

I don't know if there is anything different in 4.7 since it's been long that I last worked with RFIDeas SDK. I know that there was some work done for supporting a new RFIDeas model(s), but don't know if that could have any impact. In general as we know, RFIDeas device configuration can be changed due to multiple commands coming to the device fast one after another - which can happen with network latency, but I don't know if this is the case here. There is some code path when we set the invert bits flag, but we haven't seen that issue before.

I think the best way is to open a case with our support and then it will come to the appropriate engineers.

Misha



From: Paul Srisoontorn [mailto:psrisoontorn@teradici.com]
Sent: Thursday, April 18, 2013 18:12
To: Michael Michlin
Subject: Inverted prox card ID on tap-out

Hi Misha,

I'm investigating an issue where the prox card ID on tap-out is not the same as the tap-in ID. This causes the Zero Client to prompt the user to re-enrol the same card again. This issue was reported by one of our customers. It is also the same issue that we ran into at HIMMS after upgrading to OneSign 4.7. However, we were not able to reproduce the same issue here in our lab.

I looked at the Zero Client's log from the customer and found that the Invert Wiegand data setting on the prox reader was changed from "On" to "Off" while in session.
Note: The Zero Client doesn't touch the configuration of the prox reader at all while in session. In fact, in FW 4.1, we don't touch the Invert Wiegand setting at all even in pre-session.

The log file from the customer shows that the card ID read by the Zero Client on tap-in is: "023087F3" and the Invert Wiegand Data setting was set to "On" before going into session. On tap-out, the card ID that the OneSign agent sent to the Zero Client over VCHAN is: "01CF780C". Note: This card ID is inverted.

01CF780C = 01110011110111100000001100b    (tap-out ID)

023087F3 = 10001100001000011111110011b     (tap-in ID)

At some point while in session, the Invert Wiegand setting on the prox reader got changed from "On" to "Off".

This issue is not reproducible all the time. The customer was able to reproduce this issue after ~20 tap-in / tap-out. The reader that they are using is: RFIDeas RDR-6082.

Have you seen this issue before on your end? Is there anything different in OneSign 4.7 that could cause this issue? Please let me know if you have an idea on how to troubleshoot this issue further.


Thanks,

Paul
